SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient vaccinated and complained initially of tingling sensation in fingertips at 1025.  Patient went to bathroom 10 minutes later.  At 1045 patient began complaining of coughing, throat was "tight", face was visibly flushed.  RN called Pharmacist requesting Benadryl.  Patient declined the liquid Benadryl offered by the pharmacist.  Patient had her own Benadryl 25 mg tablets in her car.  She agreed to take one 25 mg Benadryl po at 1050.  Patient normally takes 50 mg po every day and wanted to take another dose so she did at 1053.  Pulse was 60 and regular.  Patient did have relief of symptoms, decreased flushing, decreased throat tightness, and more calm after 30 minutes.  Patient agreed to wait awhile longer.  She was encouraged to follow up with her primary care doctor to discuss reactions and to determine how to proceed regarding getting a second dose of Pfizer vaccine.  At 1215 patient felt fine to drive home.  She was accompanied by her son.  RN to call patient later to see how she is feeling.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the first shot of Pfizer Covid Vaccine at 10:00 AM on 3/21/21.  Aside from some drowsiness I felt fine the entire day. After that the pain transitioned to the back of my calf muscle for the next few days.  The pain then went back to my knee for a day and then returned to the back of my calf muscle.  On 3/30/21 I saw my primary care physician who then sent me to get an ultrasound which determined that the pain in my knee and calf were caused by blood clots (DVT).  I was then prescribed Eliquis 5 mg blood thinners.

Hematologist/oncologist diagnosed patient on 4/12/21 with hemophagocytic lympohistiocytosis (HLH) with CNS involvement.  Patient met 6/8 HLH-2004 diagnostic criteria.  6/8 results were able to be evaluated; awaiting 2/8 evaluable.   Probability per provider of having HLH is greater than 99%  using the validated H Score.   The trigger for the HLH appears to be deranged immune activation by the COVID-19 vaccine within the setting of prolonged immunosuppression for transplanted heart.    Due to presenting with severe headache and elevated protein in CSF = Intrathecal chemotherapy was initiated.    Treatment:  HLH-94 Regimen  Dexamethasone  Etoposide  Possible Rituximab  - will only start if EBV DNA is positive
LAB_DATA: HLH  2004 Diagnostic criteria (5 must be met)  Fever greater than 38.5 Hepatomegaly  or splenomegaly At least 2 significant peripheral blood cytopenias Ferritin > 500  Elevated triglycerides >265 or low fibrinogen <150 mg/Dl Hemophagocytes in bone marrow or other organ tissue  4/9 Surgical pathology report + hemophagocytosis  4/9 TG 300  Ferritin 36100 on 4/9/2021

Before I went to bed at around 11:30pm the day of my shot (4/13), I took one extra strength tylenol as prevention. I woke up around 2:40am 4/14 trembling as if I was having a seizure (it did not feel like chills) and extreme aches. I took my temperature and was at 100.8. I took another extra strength tylenol and tried to calm down. At around 3:30 the trembling stopped and I was finally able to relax a bit. I fell back asleep around 5am and woke up at 9:00am with more extreme aches and pain. I switched to ibuprofen (400mg) and that worked way better. My fever was at 101.8 when I woke up. Around mid morning and afternoon I was feeling fine just a bit achy and fatigued and my fever broke to 99. I took a nap around 2pm and woke up feeling bad again with a fever of 100.6. I took another 400mg of ibuprofen and that got me through my class and the evening feeling okay. Before bed, I was feeling achy and fatigued yet again. I took 200mg of ibuprofen and went to bed just fine. I woke up at 4:30am 4/15 for my clinical feeling back to normal. I have been fine ever since.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient developed mild case of Guillain Barre Syndrome 34 hours after injection of the Johnson and Johnson vaccine. Patient has severe extremity pains. The patient has a personal history of being diagnosed with Guillain-Barre after a yellow fever vaccination.
LAB_DATA: He received IV Toradol to help out with his extremity pain. Labs were checked to rule out electrolyte disturbance, thrombocytopenia. The patient's neurologic examination does not demonstrate classic signs of Guillain-Barre, there is no evidence of muscle weakness or paralysis and his deep tendon reflexes are normal. Acute pain has been described in acute Guillain-Barre, and so I gave the patient return precautions regarding progressive symptoms. At this point, there are not enough objective criteria to diagnose him with GBS, symptoms do not suggest the need for hospitalization for observation.  Even so, it is clear the severe extremity pain is a result of the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D, K,  Vitamin B complex Multivitamin  Fish Oil

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Two days following first dose Moderna Vaccine at Pharmacy, she suffered a cardiac arrest.  Below  Discharge Summary From 3/26 hospital.   Patient PCP Information Provider PCP Type DO General Discharge Summary by DO at 3/26/2021 12:42 PM Author: DO Service: Cardiology Author Type: Resident Filed: 3/26/2021 12:57 PM Date of Service: 3/26/2021 12:42 PM Status: Attested Editor: DO (Resident) Cosigner: MD at 3/26/2021 1:17 PM  Resident Attestation: I personally saw and examined the patient on rounds with my cariology resident team on the day of the resident's note. Management was discussed with the cardiology resident and I supervised the plan of care. I have reviewed and agree with the key parts of the resident evaluation including:  Subjective information Objective findings on physical exam Impression and plan Gen: appears comfortable, sitting in bed Resp: clear. no wheezes, rhonchi, rales CV: normal rate, regular, no m/r/g Abd: soft, nt/nd Ext: warm, no edema. Pressure ulcer boots on. Pleasant 70-year-old woman who had a history of PVCs, left bundle branch block, and a mild nonischemic cardiomyopathy, came into the hospital following a VT/VF cardiac arrest. Her echocardiogram done while in the hospital showed a preserved ejection fraction. Her cardiac catheterization showed normal coronary arteries. She had implantation of an ICD. Hospital course has been complicated by watershed cerebral infarcts. In addition, she had an episode of C. difficile colitis. She has gradually improved over the course of the past 3 weeks. From a cardiovascular perspective, she is being discharged on carvedilol 25 mg twice a day, lisinopril 10 mg daily, and her home atorvastatin. With regards to her etiology of cardiac arrest, I would be suspicious about the possibility of sarcoidosis. However, we were not able to get a cardiac MR while she was inpatient due to her strokes and inability to consistently follow commands and hold her breath. Would recommend consideration of an outpatient. She is ready to discharge to subacute rehab today. I have spent greater than 30 minutes in discharge planning.  Preferred Name: PATIENT  PCP: DO Primary Cardiologist:  MD Discharging Cardiologist: MD Admission Date: 3/5/2021 Admission Diagnosis: Cardiac arrest  Discharge Date: 03/26/21 Discharge Summary Author:  DO Primary Discharge Diagnosis VT/VF cardiac arrest, s/p therapeutic hypothermia S/p AICD placement 3/16/2021 Secondary Discharge Diagnoses Anoxic brain injury, recovering, with persistent aphasia and dysphagia C. difficile colitis Non-sustained ventricular tachycardia, resolved DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY Presenting Problem/History of Present Illness Patient is a 70 y.o. female, with history of nonischemic cardiomyopathy, admitted on 3/5/2021 after out of hospital VT/VF cardiac arrest. She completed therapeutic hypothermia protocol. Cardiac catheterization did not show any significant obstructive coronary disease. TTE showed LVEF 55%. Patient underwent AICD placement on 3/16/2021. Had some recurrent nonsustained ventricular tachycardia afterward, which resolved after increasing her carvedilol doses. Her course was complicated by a C. difficile infection, treated with PO Vancomycin, with significant improvement in diarrhea. She has had gradual neurologic recovery. Neurology felt she had had several watershed infarcts, but felt that she would continue to have a prolonged recovery over the next few months. Had some recovery of language/cognition prior to discharge. Due to her waxing/waning encephalopathy, she did not qualify for inpatient rehab, but will be discharged to subacute rehab. Discharged with tube feeding continued, though she can begin sips with speech therapy supervision. Patient seen and examined at bedside on the day of discharge. She stated that she had no pain, though HPI/ROS still limited due to aphasia. Discussed above information with patient's husband, who understood and was in agreement with the plan.  Problem-Based Hospital Course NEURO Acute metabolic encephalopathy, with gradual recovery -Due to neurologic injury from cardiac arrest. -Neurology consult: concern for anoxic brain injury with watershed infarcts, anticipate very gradual recovery over the coming months. No acute process on imaging. -Patient extubated on 3/11, following some commands. Continuing to regain conversational ability and motor function gradually each day. Has some waxing and waning of mental status, but overall her encephalopathy  continues to improve. -Limit centrally acting/sedating medications -Speech following for language/cognition as well as dysphagia requiring tube feeding. Headache and general tiredness began 30-45 min after shot.  Muscle soreness (injection site, rib muscles, leg muscles, back muscles and neck muscles) began soon after.  By 6pm, muscles had become painful.  I had chills but no measurable fever.  I got in the bed but unable to sleep due to muscle pain and discomfort.  Hip joints and back began to ache.  Fever and chills worsened over the next several hours to measurable with highest at 102F.  I took 1000mg tylenol generic which did not lower fever but fever did not rise higher.  Throughout the night, I experienced calf muscle cramps and foot cramps, stomach pains, joint pains, inability to sleep, worsening injection site soreness and armpit soreness (likely lymph node soreness).  Once in middle of night I may have felt chest tightness but I even doubted that I really experienced it as I had been thinking about all the AEs I was experiencing.  Symptoms continued through night.  Next morning, developed a cough so I made appointment to get a COVID exposure test at 1pm on 13th April because I had flown in plane on 10th April.   Cough could have been due to allergy type post-nasal drip because of high pollen in area.  By late Tue evening, I felt better.  Headache had resolved and muscle symptoms improved.  Now (3:45pm on 15th April) I am still experiencing lymph node/armpit soreness and general inability to focus, think clearly.  I feel like I am in a fog.  I emailed a message to my physician and reported this through VAERS
LAB_DATA: 13th April - COVID 19 test - results returned on 15th April as negative.
OTHER_MEDS: Cosentyx and Mirena (no OTC, dietary supplements or herbal remedies)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Verified the patient by full name and date of birth.  Explained the immunizations that are due to be given today.  Mother of patient was given the vaccine information sheets for each vaccine.  Administered vaccines at 1150am.  I came back to the exam room, and the mother stated that the patient leg was not looking right.  I visualized a circular red area approx. 7-8 cm.  The patient was not in distress.  She was sitting up on the table licking a lollipop.  Mom asked her 3 times what does you leg feel like.  The patient answered after the third question stating it hurts.  She said it did not itch after I asked her.  Called the providers nurse, and the provider was in the room with her nurse.  I informed her that the patient had a localized reaction to the MMRV vaccine, and if she could come to the room to examine the area.  Provider came to the room within 1 min of the call and examined the area.   Provider asked the patient if the area was itching.  The patient responded by saying no.  The provider informed the mother that the area looked like a localized reaction to the injection site.  Mom verbalized an understanding.  Provider informed the mother to continue waiting the 15 mins after vaccine administration.  Mom verbalized an understanding.   Patient ambulated to the lobby and left with her mother following the 15 min wait time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received his 2nd dose of the Pfizer vaccine at on Monday, February 15. That evening, he experienced visual disturbances with slightly blurred vision. Not thinking anything of it at the time, the vision cleared, and he continued about their evening/week without telling anyone of his visual disturbances. On Sunday, February 21, he experienced additional visual disturbances including double vision and dizziness, and we had him visit a local ER for evaluation. He was discharged with a diagnosis of dehydration and vertigo. No scans were performed. The visual disturbances cleared up the following week and the only persistent symptom was a slight dizziness. An eye exam was performed on Friday, February 26 with no problems found. An MRI was performed on March 3, and he was diagnosed with the below conditions.   Impression (3/3/2021) 1. Small acute to subacute infarcts in the left splenium of the corpus callosum and parasagittal left occipital lobe. 2. Trace subarachnoid hemorrhage in the parasagittal left parietal lobe. 3. Mild chronic microvascular ischemic disease.  He was admitted to the hospital and remained there until Saturday, March 6. Follow-up scans and testing were performed with no underlying reason for the stroke being determined. Prior to the stroke, he had been a very active individual with osteoarthritis as is only health complaint. He was not on any prescription medication prior to the stroke. While in the hospital, the tests for high blood pressure, high cholesterol (LDL 92 MG/DL), sugar inadequacies (glucose 93 mg/dl, A1C 5.7%), etc. came back without major concerns. His follow-up CT scans also did not reveal the stroke shown on the MRI. No inquiry was made by any of his doctors or hospital staff as to his COVID vaccination status/dates to even consider the connection. Below are the results of the last CT scans:  Impression (3/4/2021) 1. Age-related volume loss and white matter disease similar to prior exams. 2. Small infarct seen on MRI are not well seen on CT. 3. No acute intracranial abnormality demonstrated on the CT scan.  Impression (3/5/2021) 1. No evidence of acute infarct or intracranial hemorrhage. No significant change. 2. Periventricular white matter disease is likely secondary to chronic small vessel ischemic changes.
LAB_DATA: 2/21/2021 - In ER, EKG, Bloodwork for Magnesium, Metabolic Panel (Basic), CBC w/o Diff, Chest X-ray 2/26/2021 - Eye exam - Glaucoma screening 3/1/2021 - Urinalysis,  Metabolic Panel (Basic) 3/3/2021 - MRI Brain w & w/o contrast 3/4/2021 - Metabolic panel (comprehensive), CBS w/ automated Diff, CTA Head, CTA Neck, CT Head w/o contrast,  3/5/2021 - Troponin-I, CK, Lipase, Phosphorus, Magnesium, Metabolic Panel (Basic), TSH 3rd Generation, SED Rate (ESR), CBC w/o Diff, Hemoglobin A1C with EAG,  Lipid Panel, CT Head w/o contrast, Echocardiogram

About three hours after the vaccination, after eating a light dinner of two pieces of pizza and drinking a beer (to celebrate,  I thought) (an identical dinner to my husband, who was vaccinated minutes after me, and who suffered no adverse effects) I suddenly had extreme nausea and, immediately, projectile vomiting. My entire stomach emptied, but I continued to retch for the entire night and into the next day, weak and nauseated for about 72 hours. I became dehydrated but couldn't keep water down for 48 hours.   That first night, I experienced body temperature swings, whole body pain (not muscle aches, and not localized) and most disturbingly, hallucinations.  I awoke in the middle of the night convinced that my body had stretched in length  and there were two of me.  This was similar to the reaction I had to opiodes, but even worse (I didn't think anything could be worse).
LAB_DATA: none....my husband monitored me when I was out of my mind, and since he had seen me recover from the opiode reaction, he expected the same with this situation.  The whole body pain subsided by the second day.  The nausea was severe and unrelenting, but I could drink water by the end of 48 hours.
OTHER_MEDS: levothyroxine, low dose aspirin, statin, vit D
HISTORY: thyroid function is low,  possible autoimmune cause Irritable bowel syndrome, cured by SSRIs about eight years ago some arthritis in wrists
ALLERGIES: rash to penicillin (50 years ago),  violent vomiting, nausea and fatigue from two weeks of codeine and fentanyl prescribed for neck pain one year ago (surgery took care of the slipped disc, and no opiodes were used during surgery, thus absolutely no side effects from the anesthesia, unlike prior surgeries )

These symptoms ended almost exactly 24 hours later, around 11pm the following day.  However, 24 hours after the symptoms arose,  I noticed a patchy, itchy rash covering the left side of my stomach. After the first dose, I had gotten a small circular rash on my left forearm, but at the time did not realize that was a symptom. After the 2nd dose,  the spot on my left forearm came back and was bigger. I was generally itchy and the next day noticed the rash had spread a tiny bit to my lower back.   It has been 2 weeks and my rash is still present, but significantly faded. It only itches when I touch it.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the J&J vaccine on Sunday afternoon, when my husband got up on Monday morning he passed out in the bathroom and was unresponsive. I received my  first dose of the vaccine on Wednesday, April 7th.   Later that day, my shoulder began hurting- and the pain progressed rapidly.   After struggling to fall asleep, I woke up in the middle of the night in excruciating pain.  I couldn?t  move my arm forward, back, or to the side without extreme pain.  The pain was so bad, I felt nauseated and felt like I was going to pass out.  I was unable to go back to sleep.   I expected some arm pain and soreness with this vaccine, but nothing like this.    I have not been able to move my arm since  without wanting to scream in pain from the shoulder pain.   I cannot lift my arm to change, and haven?t been able to sleep without medicine.  I honestly don?t feel this is normal vaccine arm soreness.  The injection was very high up on my shoulder.   I scheduled an appointment with an orthopedic shoulder specialist right away- who prescribed a couple of different medicines for relief.   He ordered an MRI which will be done tomorrow.  I cannot complete normal every day routine activities because I can?t move my arm and am in extreme pain.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per RN  report: patient  received dose 1 of the Moderna COVID vaccine (lot 041B21A, exp 5/6/2021) at 1023. At 1025, EMT shouted across the room to RN  "she's going to faint." RN  approached patient to assess, the patient was diaphoretic, pale, and not responding to questions or making eye contact. RN  squeezed her hand and patient made eye contact and verbalized feeling lightheaded. RN , EMT , and EMT  transferred the patient to a zero-gravity chair allowing patient to recline. RN returned from helping outside and approached to assist at RN  was taking care of another patient. At 1027, patient reported feeling faint, sweaty, with blurry vision, and ringing in the ears. Vital signs: 94/62, pulse 72, O2 93, respirations 22. Patient denied nausea, reported she had eaten breakfast that morning. Patient reported having a similar reaction when she donated blood previously. Patient denied allergies, medical conditions, or taking any medications. At 1035, vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 68, blood pressure 104/62, respirations 22. PHN  offered Benadryl but patient declined. PHN  encouraged patient to contact provider and when to call 911. At 1042, vital signs: blood pressure 98/62, O2 99%, pulse 74, respirations 22. Patient reported that she was experiencing numbness in both hands. At 1049, patient reported her symptoms were improving including the numbness in her hands, blurry vision, and lightheadedness. Patient reported feeling cold, weak, and shaky. PHN  noted patient's facial color was returning. At 1054, vital signs: blood pressure 100/62, O2 99%, pulse 68, respirations 20. Patient reported her symptoms has resolved at this point. At 1059, vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 69, respirations 18, blood pressure 110/64. PHN  and EMT  assisted patient to seated position. At 1105, patient stood up with PHN  and EMT  close by. Patient reported no symptoms and back to her baseline. At 1108, EMT  walked patient out. Patient left walking with steady gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Thursday , March 18th 2021, at 10.20 a.m., right after the vaccination my hand started to be very painful. I got the vaccine at work and I continued to work, but about 2.00 p.m. I got a headache. I finished with work at 3.30 p.m. and I went to our nurse at work. She gave me some painkillers. When I came home, the headache was getting worse and I started to shake. My whole body was shaking and I got a fever. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot EW0150, exp 7/2021) dose 1 at 1400. At 1405, EMT approached patient who appeared pale and diaphoretic with his eyes closed. PHN approached to assess, patient had slow speech and pulse felt thready. Vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 56, respirations 24. Patient had thick sweatshirt on EMT had difficulty obtaining blood pressure. Paramedic approached to assist. At 1410, PHN, EMT, and paramedic transfered patient to zero gravity chair and placed in reclining position. Patient was offered water and he verbalized feeling better. Patient denied allergies, medical conditions, or medications. PHN assisted patient in removing sweatshirt partially to obtain blood pressure. Vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 51, blood pressure 92/60, respirations 24. PHN offered Benadryl but patient declined. PHN advised on when to call 911. At 1422, patient reported light sensitivity and blurry vision. At 1425, vital signs: pulse 52, respirations 18, O2 99%, blood pressure 118/84. At 1535, vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 58, respirations 18, blood pressure 110/66. Patient reported continued improvement in symptoms, only feeling tired. Patient reported working out, only sleeping 2 hours that night, and not eating before coming in. PHN called family member at patient's request to drive patient home. At 1439, patient assisted to seated position in zero-gravity chair by PHN and EMT. Patient reported symptoms had resolved and he felt back to baseline. At 1445, patient stood up, monitored closely by PHN and EMT. At 1449, patient left walking with steady gait to parking lot where family member was waiting to drive patient home.

Pain level went from previous day, level 1 of 10 during ambulation or PT (no post-op analgesics or antiinflammatory drugs had been taken for several days at that point) to level 7.  In addition, the right (non-operated) knee flared up with persistent pain (pain in that knee previously was only occasional), and arthritic pain in both hands increased.  (I don't normally take analgesics or antiinflammatory drugs for arthritis pain.)  I had also had two days of fatigue following vaccination.  On the day after this increase in pain, I had chills and fever - a low-grade temp of 100 via temporal scanner, on that day only.  PT continued, along with Tylenol and ice for pain. After patient received his shot, while sitting during the 15 min waiting period. The patient began getting lightheaded and hot, his color went out of him and his eyes began rolling back in his head.  His eyelids turned a purple color and he appeared to momentarily stop breathing.  Myself and another pharmacist got him on the ground and supported his head with a coat.  When he "came to" and was talking to us.  He described feeling better on the cold floor and his color began coming back.   I was speaking with him the entire time.  While we were out with his 9-1-1 was called and paramedics arrived 15 min later.  by the time paramedics had arrived the patient had gotten up and back into the chair himself, was lucid and had color back in his face.  Paramedics arrived and took over.  He was given the green light from them and remained in the pharmacy area for a total of about 30 minutes before heading home. The patient was admittedly nervous for the shot and had not eaten or had anything to drink the whole day to that point. I believe he passed out from a variety of factors not related to the actual ingredients in the vaccine but cannot confirm this.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received  her first COVID vaccine on Thursday, March 18.  On 3/23/21 she started to have new onset of generalized muscles aches and weakness.  She started feeling some pain in her back, which then spread to arms and legs. She is now beginning to feel weakness in her core and extremities. Having difficulty lifting arms above head. She is still able to walk without difficulty but legs do feel weak. Increase in SOB as well. Myalgias and chest pain resolved within a week, however she continued to feel weak, tired, and had DOE. She developed "brain fog" and talked to her boss about taking short-term disability as it had been hard to work.  No appetite. On 4/1/21, she presented to the ED with 2 weeks of worsening generalized weakness, SOB, lightheadedness, dizziness and found to have acute anemia. Was admitted for further workup.  Hgb at admission was 5.4.   This admission diagnosed her with a new warm autoantibody hemolytic anemia. This is new since the COVID vaccine was administered.  Upon admission there was no thrombocytopenia, so there was low suspicion for microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, TTP/HUS, or DIC. Peripheral blood smear at that time suggested a leukoerythroblastic blood picture (could be Bone Marrow recovery post chemo) but with marked normocytic, normochromic anemia, and with increased circulating erythroid precursors and increased red blood cell regeneration; spherocytes and fragments are present supporting hemolysis.  DAT positive (both IgG and C3) along with other hemolysis lab including elevated LDH, Bilirubin, haptoglobin 3, and PBS c/w hemolysis; no evidence of MAHA. So warm autoantibody hemolytic anemia is the most likely explanation. She had negative cold agglutinin antibodies <1:32 on 4/9. Started on methylprednisolone on 4/2/21, but Hgb continued to steadily decline despite treatment. Continued on methylprednisolone 87.5mg daily. Rituxan 375mg/m2 was started on 4/6/21 with plans for weekly infusions for a total of 4 weeks.  there was concern for a GI bleed on 4/10-4/11 due to bright red fluid appearing like blood in the toilet after a stool. This led to her receiving roughly 5 units of pRBCs. After these 5 units she started urinating red urine and we became highly concerned for hyperhemolysis. She did not have any further stools so we did not think a GI bleed was likely.    She was given 1 dose of Eculizumab (Soliris) (4/12). This treatment is for complement mediated intravascular hyperhemolysis. Unfortunately it did not appear to help her.   On 4/14, we were thinking TTP could be contributory with numerous schistocytes on peripheral smear. Her T bili was up to 7.8, and her hemoglobin plasma was trending up, in the 380 -- > 610 and in the 800s today. Cr was worsening. Platelet count was dropping.  With her worsening condition and concern for both hyperhemolysis and possible TTP, we decided to start her plasma exchange followed by her second dose of Rituximab.  Unfortunately she became disoriented/confused following line placement and while receiving plasmaphoresis. CT head returned without acute findings. She then had an allergic reaction with a rash during PLEX which was stopped (4L completed with a goal of 5L). Improved with benadryl.  She was then administered rituximab. Then she developed worsening sinus tachycardia and HTN.   Her respiratory status deteriorated and she eventually required high-flow oxygen to maintain saturations > 90%. CXR showed bilateral opacities, not drastically changed from previous films. Rituximab was stopped halfway through its infusion in case this was an adverse effect to the drug. She was given 20 mg IV Lasix per the nighttime sign-out. She was initially given ceftriaxone and azithromycin IV to cover CAP but later ABx were broadened to vanc and Zosyn with rising lactate of unknown source.   Ultimately she had acute respiratory failure with hypoxia and need BiPAP. She was eventually intubated and a code blue was called.  She unfortunately died shortly after intubation.
OTHER_MEDS: Albuterol 108 MCG/ACT inhaler - Inhale 1-2 puffs into the lungs every 4 hours as needed  Ascorbic Acid (VITAMIN C GUMMIE PO) 100 mg daily atorvastatin (LIPITOR) 40 MG tablet dao;y beclomethasone HFA (QVAR REDIHALER) 80 MCG/ACT inhaler - two

SYMPTOM_TEXT: During the week of 3/29/21 (the week following my vaccine), I began to experience periodic lower abdominal pain (lower right and lower center) during movement (walking or going from sitting to standing.   On Monday, 4/5/21 (13 days after my vaccine), I began experiencing severe abdominal pain upon getting out of bed at 7am.  The pain was worse with movement of any kind (walking, turning, going from sitting to standing).  I was convinced something was seriously wrong, and called my Dr's office .  While waiting for the NP to call me, I decided that I should go to the hospital.  My husband drove me, and even the car ride there was painful (bumps and turns).  The pain upon standing was as if my bladder was going to fall out.  The pain when walking was a stabbing type of pain in my lower right abdomen and a stretching sensation in my center/lower abdomen. The E.R. Dr  diagnosed me with epiplogic appendagitis, and instructed me to rest, hydrate, and take tylenol. I followed the Drs advice.  I took 4/5&6 off from work, spending most of that time in a reclining position in my livingroom and I drank plenty of water. I felt noticeable improvements daily.  I saw my PCP  for a follow-up visit on 4/8 for an abdominal exam, at which time I was experiencing pain primarily in bed (in a stretched out position) and periodically with movement (walking and going from sitting to standing or turning).  I had my second follow-up today with my PCP (4/15).  I continue to improve daily.
LAB_DATA: Blood work (basic metabolic panel; cbc auto differential; hepatic function panel; lipase; magnesium; troponin); Urinalysis w/reflex to microscopic  & culture; CT abdomen pelvis with contrast; ECG 12 lead

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient brought into clinic by mother for immunizations and patient needing PPD placed for school. Patient due for HPV, FLU, and MEN-B. Handouts given and reviewed with mother and patient. Mom agreeable to all vaccines but let patient decide about the HPV vaccine, mother had previously declined that vaccine for patient. Educated on HPV disease and vaccine, patient opted to receive HPV vaccine and mother supported that decision. Patient declined travel to high risk TB areas, signs/symptoms of TB, past exposure, or past positive PPD. Placed PPD on L. forearm. Patient tolerated well. Instructed patient and mother on PPD reading instructing to have it read by instructor or ER nurse in 48-72hours, as clinic will not be open on Saturday or Sunday. School requires 2-step manteaux, instructed patient to come back 1 week after first PPD is read to get 2nd PPD placed. Vaccine history form filled out for patient for school program.  Administered Flu shot and HPV vaccine in L. deltoid at 1146. After receiving HPV vaccine patient fainted with eyes rolling back and made a few involuntary jerky movements and body going limp. Cleared exam bed and mother of patient eased patient to lay down on exam bed, preventing patient from falling. Patient's gaze returned within seconds and patient tried to sit up. Mother and self coaxed patient to remain laying down and take slow deep breaths. Called supervisor for immediate assistance, getting snacks and juice for patient to drink, while I stayed with patient. Checked patient's vital signs temp 99.1F, Heart rate 82, BP (supine) 128/84, and respiratory rate 20, O2 saturation 100%. Supervisor opened window in exam room to let in some fresh cool air. Patient took a few sips of juice and a piece of chocolate. Patient reported feeling ok, but didn't know what happened. Self and supervisor reviewed with patient and mom that fainting after vaccines is common especially for teens, and patient hadn't eaten anything yet today. Observed patient for a few more minutes, and then had patient sit up. Checked vital signs again with patient sitting @ 1149 BP 124/81, 99.2F, HR 80, resp rate 18, O2 sats 99%. Patient took a few more sips of juice and declined anymore snacks. She stated she was feeling well. Self and supervisor still encouraged mom and patient to continue with vaccine series, reviewing external factors that can lead to fainting and still weighing the risk of the disease and vaccine reaction. Encouraging patient to eat prior to getting vaccines in the future.  Mother of patient opted not to give patient anymore shots at this visit. Instructed to patient and mother that patient did not receive the MEN B at this visit, so patient will still be due for that vaccine. Will consider receiving the vaccine in the future.  Patient feeling ok and ready to go home, instructed patient to stand up slowly, mother at patient's side for patient's assistance. Patient steady on her feet. Walked patient and mother out of office and encouraged to call with any questions/concerns.
Throat closed up 30 minutes after and one day after.
OTHER_MEDS: Ritual multivitamin for women Vegan omega 3 Depo provera shot

Wednesday, March 31, 2021 Moderna vaccine, 2nd shot at 4:00pm. Arm began to feel sore about 10pm. Blood pressure and oximeter reading remained normal throughout.  Thursday, April 1, 2021 Insufficient sleep, sudden increase in sinus congestion, muscle soreness and increasingly sore arm upon arising. Fatigue, Imbalance and Brain Fog rapidly increased. Urinary incontinence 3 times - once upon awakening and twice in the afternoon. Temperature began rising and reached 100.2�F by 3:00pm (normal temp 97.5�F). Resting pulse rate 74 at 10pm (normal 54). Headache and weakness in the evening.  Friday, April 2, 2021 Insufficient sleep, sore arm, sinus congestion, sneezing, moderate headache, moderate imbalance, muscle soreness, weak, moderate brain fog. Resting pulse rate 64 (normal 54). Temp at 7:30am 99.4�F (normal 97.5�F). NEW today: joint pain in both hips and Tinnitus suddenly spiking high. 10:00pm noticed mood began to change, feelings of irritation then anger for no apparent reason.  *Saturday, April 3, 2021 Insufficient sleep. Temperature at 12:30pm 98.1�F then continued to fall until it reached normal range (97.7�F) at 10:00pm. Resting pulse rate 68 (normal 54). Increasingly painful hip joints, sinus congestion still high, sneezing, mild headache, canker sores, tinnitus spiking, brain fog, increased imbalance. *NEW today: 7:30am-10:00am mental confusion, hallucinations, auditory, increased imbalance. Afterwards, feelings of fear, anger and paranoia that persisted through Sunday. Evening: increasing blurred vision and diplopia (both chronic conditions but usually very mild). Injection site suddenly red and more swollen, itching. Still feeling uncharacteristically emotional at bedtime.  Sunday, April 4, 2021 Insomnia. Volatile emotions - anger, agitation, crying - kept me awake Saturday night; slept 2:30am-8:30am Sunday morning. Brain fog, imbalance, sinus congestion, sneezing, right arm itching, hip joint pain, canker sores on tongue, spiking tinnitus continue. Temperature normal all day; resting pulse rate still high 64 (normal 54).  Monday April 5 through Thursday April 15: Most symptoms continued to gradually subside over the next ten days. Spiking tinnitus, canker sores and injection site itching were the most persistent and lasted until April 15. Imbalance subsided on April 12. NEW Symptoms: Anxiety dreaming began on April 6th. Most nights had insufficient sleep. Concern about the cause of the episode of delirium on April 3rd continues. Good news, no COVID-Arm like I had with the 1st vaccination.  General observations: It seems as though my body's response to the 2nd vaccination was to temporarily trigger some of the symptoms of my chronic health conditions like MCAS, Dysautonomia and Diplopia, without causing an actual flareup of those conditions. This was quite unexpected and disconcerting. The episode of delirium was something I've never experienced and hope to never experience again.
HISTORY: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome, Dysautonomia, Venous Insufficiency, Diplopia

Last Thurs and Sat in addition to the headache, nausea, chills I was fatigued to the point where I slept 14 hours on Thurs and 16 hours on Sat.  Another symptom that I have is on my injection arm.  Occasionally it will hurt from my middle finger to my collar bone.

I experienced moderate diarrhea approximately 3 days after receiving the second dose of my Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine.  I had no other symptoms  - no upset stomach, nausea, etc.  I received my second dose at 1:30p.m. on 4/2, and the diarrhea started at 5:00p.m. on April 5.  It was essentially water, and I had about 4 watery bowel-movements that evening and one the next day.  Around 2:00p.m. on April 6 I had a bowel movement that was more solid in consistency, and by the next day I was having regular bowel movements.  I had a somewhat upset stomach on April 6, but up until that point I did not have any other symptoms.  I do not believe that this was caused by anything I ate.

My period started on the expected day, April 1st 2021 and it has not stopped (15 days as of now) and is excessively heavy with extremely large clots every day. I have not yet seen a doctor as I do not currently have health insurance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 2:43pm patient received the vaccine in her arm. At 2:50pm my pharmacy technician witnessed the patient standing up from her chair and walk up to the pharmacy counter then faint into the pharmacy immunization booth. My technician states the patient did not hit her head on a wall. At 2:51pm my pharmacy technician brought the incident to my attention and we both ran to the patient to address the situation.  The patient was unresponsive, so I ran and dial 911 then instructed my tech to take the phone. I then ran back to the patient and patted her back, said her name and asked her if she could hear me.  It was at that moment the patient's eyes flickered and the patient had what looked to me like a 10 second seizure in the chair inside the pharmacy booth.  Once the patient was done what I could only identify as seizing, she came to and I asked her if she new her name and where she was. The patient answered correctly and then asked me "Have you had anyone with a reaction like this before?". I answered that I have not personally witnessed a reaction like this before. My technician had 911 still on the phone and they instructed her to stand out front of the store to await the ambulance. A first responding officer came in and asked about the witnesses to the incident then took over for caring for the patient.
HISTORY: Patient reported that she has had one seizure in the past. She stated that she has not had one in a long time and no longer took medication to treat them. The one seizure she did have was unrelated to a vaccine.

Around 4-5 hours after receiving injection, I noticed two large lumps at the base of my buttocks that were never there before, just inside the crack below my spine.  These lumps are about the size of a small lemon and hard, not soft like a cyst would be.  I Googled it and saw that we have lumph nodes all throughout our bodies, even in that area, and when I called my doctor, he told me to take Benedryl and to come in and see him the following week.  I have read of many side effects of these vaccinations, but nothing like this!

bruises are darker than normal since he has started Eliquis; Constipation; swollen index finger and swollen toe/determined to be gout; felt lousy; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer.  This spontaneous case was reported by a physician and describes the occurrence of GOUT (swollen index finger and swollen toe/determined to be gout), FATIGUE (felt lousy), CONTUSION (bruises are darker than normal since he has started Eliquis) and CONSTIPATION in 92-year-old male patient who received apixaban (Eliquis) tablet (batch no. 1790398) for Venous thromboembolism. CO-SUSPECT PRODUCTS included Covid-19 Vaccine for an unknown indication. The patient's past medical history included Large intestine infection, Hypercoagulability and Constipation. Concurrent medical conditions included Gout. In February 2021, the patient started Eliquis (batch no. 1790398) (Oral) at an unspecified dose twice a day. On an unknown date, the patient started Covid-19 Vaccine (unknown route). On 27-Mar-2021, the patient experienced FATIGUE (felt lousy). On 29-Mar-2021, the patient experienced GOUT (swollen index finger and swollen toe/determined to be gout). On an unknown date, the patient experienced CONTUSION (bruises are darker than normal since he has started Eliquis) and CONSTIPATION. The action taken with Eliquis(Oral) was unknown. At the time of the report, GOUT, CONTUSION and CONSTIPATION outcome was unknown and FATIGUE resolved. For Eliquis(Oral), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. The reporter stated that he was put on Eliquis for ninety days and has used it for thirty days so far. He has had some issues that require an enema. Concomitant medications included: dark Cherry Extract - started on or after 29-Mar-2021. The reporter stated that he had been taking Eliquis for 45 days for blood clots that stemmed from a colon infection with secondary hypercoagulability. On Saturday 27-Mar-2021, the patient had his second injection of the Pfizer Covid vaccine. After receiving the vaccine, he said he felt lousy and had common side effects for a vaccine that lasted for about 2 days. On 29-Mar-2021 he woke up with a swollen index finger and swollen toe and this was determined to be gout. The gout in his index finger he had before. The patient stated that whenever he got bruises he had noticed that the bruises were darker than normal since he had started Eliquis. The patient also stated that he has had considerable constipation that started before Eliquis, but still persisted at times and he had treated with enemas. Patient was a retired physician.   Follow-up (30Mar2021): This is a follow-up spontaneous report from a contactable physician, based on information received by Pfizer  Most recent follow-up information was received from a physician on 30-Mar-2021 included the following: the event adverse event nos was amended as information on adverse events were received, new events and suspect product added, patient attributes, medical history, product attributes and narrative updated.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Constipation; Hypercoagulability; Large intestine infection

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient advised she took COVID-19 Vaccine and formed blood clots in leg; This is a solicited report from a non-Pfizer sponsored program: -CW2891702, received from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer from manufacturer (manufacturer control number: BMS-2021-032881), license party for apixaban.  This 86-year-old female patient was involved in a patient support program. The patient (patient ID: (ID)) received APIXABAN. The report describes a case of THROMBOSIS (Patient advised she took COVID-19 Vaccine and formed blood clots in leg). Co-suspect products included Covid-19 Vaccine for an unknown indication. On an unknown date, the patient started APIXABAN (unknown route), (unspecified dose and frequency). On an unknown date, the patient experienced THROMBOSIS (seriousness criterion medically significant). The action taken with APIXABAN (Unknown) was unknown. At the time of the report, THROMBOSIS outcome was unknown. For APIXABAN (Unknown), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. This report was received from consumer. The patient received therapy with apixaban and COVID-19 Vaccine for unknown indication. Follow-up is unable to be performed. Medical evaluation comment: This patient had blood clots in the leg after apixaban therapy. Based on the limited information regarding medical history, event details, treatment details, it cannot be ascertained that the suspect drug contributed to the reported event.  The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the event Thrombosis leg with the suspect products was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  Amgen's assessment: the event, Thrombosis leg, was assessed as unrelated to apixaban.  No follow-up attempts are possible; information about batch number cannot be obtained.; Sender's Comments: As there is limited information in the case provided, the causal association between the event of thrombosis and the suspect vaccine BNT162B2 cannot be excluded. Based on known mechanism of action of the drug, the event of thrombosis is assessed as not related to Apixaban.  The case will be reassessed once new information is available.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer drug is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

had shingles twice / Once / then several years had vaccine /Then had shingles the second time/suspected vaccination failure; shingles 2nd time; This case was reported by a consumer via (facebook) interactive digital media and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingles vaccine) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (had prior to the vaccination).   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingles vaccine. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingles vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and shingles. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and shingles were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure and shingles to be related to Shingles vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: The case was reported by the patient. The age at vaccination was not reported. The age group was not reported but it was selected as an adult as per vaccine indication. The patient had shingles twice. On 7th April 2021 06:30, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). In April 2021, 12 hrs after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced fatigue, myalgia of lower extremities, headache, lethargy, sore throat, hoarse voice and choking sensation. Additional details were reported as follows: The patient reported receiving her first dose of the Shingrix vaccine at 6:30PM. The patient stated that she does not feel right. The patient further described this feeling by describing her symptoms. She stated that on the next morning at 9:30AM, she started to have severe fatigue, muscle aches, headaches, lethargy, raspy voice, and a sore throat. She stated that her sore throat progressively worsened and she felt like she was choking on the evening of 8th April 2021 and had to drink water. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Broke out in itchy, swollen, red rash. Began as single spot on right eyelid withing 4 hours of receiving vaccine. Spread over first week, across temple and forehead and chin, later on belly (which spread to cover 1/4 torso below waist on front side), between legs on both sides at top of inner thighs, latter on outer thighs of both legs. Felt like needles pricking skin if fabric touched skin. Lasted three weeks. However, at three weeks I am sill not over the rash. I can now function normally, even though the skin is still red and slightly itchy.  Oddly, the rash was strong on the right side of my body with a fainter mirror image on the left side. I reported all this on the V-SAFE app.
LAB_DATA: On March 27, I visited a CVS clinic thinking that the rash might be Shingles and asked to get the antiviral which helps prevent Shingles only if given early. Clearly the rash was NOT Shingles because I started breaking out on other parts of my body and the rash crossed the midline. Also, I never had blisters or nerve pain as with Shingles.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: client complained of dizziness after receiving 2nd dose of Pfizer Covid Vaccine. Within 2 mins of receiving vaccine client informed RN she was feeling dizzy. Client able to transfer by herself from chair to wheelchair. RN pushed chair to observation room where EMT  assumed care. PHN  joined EMT. Client alert and oriented. Per client feeling warmth, dizzy, dry mouth. Vitals at 1434: blood pressure: 110/80, pulse 86, oxygen 98%. Medical history: diabetes, COPD, bipolar depression, glaucoma, and retinopathy. EMT gave client water. Current medications: latuda, metformin, timolol, travatan, eyedrops, novalog, basaglar, and jenuvia. Per client did not have any reaction to first dose. Client informed we would continue observing for 30 mins. 1439 client stated dizziness was improving. 1443 vitals: blood pressure: 130/80, pulse 85, oxygen 99%. Per client dizziness improving. 1448 vitals: blood pressure: 132/82, pulse 85, oxygen 100%. Client stated feeling warm again and clammy. PHN asked client to lower mask and assess skin color. Face flushed, client denies shortness of breath. Per client warmth feeling worsening, PHN offered Benadryl. Client stated not driving, insurance transport would take her home. 50mg Benadryl given orally at 1454.  Vitals: blood pressure 126/80, pulse 83, oxygen 98%. Vitals 1500: blood pressure 124/82, pulse 81, oxygen 100%. Client stated feeling better. Still warm feeling, dizziness improving. 1505 vitals: blood pressure: 122/82, pulse 83, oxygen 98%. Per client more improvement, stated starting to "feel sleepy". 1510 vitals: blood pressure 120/78, pulse 87, oxygen 97%. Per client dizziness resolved, skin color back to normal, no flushing noted. ER precautions given. Transport arrived at 1530, unable to get last set of vitals. Per client feeling much better, client asked to be wheeled to transport car due to tired feeling. PHN and EMT accompanied client to bus. Client able to stand up from chair with no complaints. Able to walk into vehicle by herself with steady gait.
OTHER_MEDS: eyedrops, timolol, travatan, latuda, jenuvia, metformin, novalog, basaglar.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At the pre-counsel stage, the patient said that he was a little nervous about getting this immunization, but wanted to go ahead and do it.  I counseled him on the immunization and sent him into the booth to get the shot.  Technician administered the vaccine and then told Technician that he felt a little nauseous.  Technician told him to stay seated.  A few seconds later the patient passed out and started slipping down the chair.  Technician grabbed him from behind and called me over to assist.  I yelled for Staff to call 9-1-1 and a code white.  I held him from the front and Technician held him from the back and we slowly lowered the patient to the floor.  Technician sat behind the patient to hold him up while I assessed the patient and tried see if he was responsive.  The patient was breathing and had a pulse, so I patted him on the face and chest to see if he would become responsive.  After about 15 seconds, the patient became responsive and confused.  He asked what happened and if he got the shot yet or not.  After talking to the patient for a moment he said he was fine, but needed to vomit.  I gave him a trash can and he vomited.  We gave the patient some water and sat with him on the ground for a few minutes until the paramedics arrived.  The paramedics took the patient's vitals and the patient said he felt fine and declined going to the hospital.  We had the patient sit in the observation area for another 30 minutes.  He said he felt totally fine and was ready to go home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt. is a 44 y.o. male evaluated with a web video visit for evaluation of side effects after undergoing the Janssen Covid-19 vaccine yesterday. He describes having systemic side effects of fever as high as 100.8F, chills, fatigue, body aches, and headache. He underwent the vaccine yesterday at approximately 1045. He denies any cutaneous, thrombohemolytic, or analphylaxis side effects.
LAB_DATA: DECISION MAKING: Adverse side effects of Covid-19 Vaccination his presentation is common for adverse effects for vaccination. He does not report any anaphylaxis or thromoemobolitic type reactions. We discussed that him adding in 600 to 800 mg of ibuprofen medication every 6 to 8 hrs to alternate with his Excedrin (caffiene, Tylenol, and ASA) medication every 4 to 6 hrs with food to avoid GI upset. I advised him to incorporate other comfort measures such as a heating pad, rest, fluids such as ginger ale, rest for the next 24 hours and that his symptoms are likely to resolve. If however they worsen he understands that he should be seen in person immediately. I encouraged him to register his symptoms with the CDC so he will have ongoing monitoring of his adverse side effects. He indicated he would do so.    1. Adverse effect of vaccine, initial encounter

I need to talk about my pfizer experience. I'm 56. January 15 I received my first dose. I had zero side effects. The night after that initial dose. I began having what I'd term as cognitive issues. Trouble focusing. Blurred vision. Confusion. My synapsis weren't synapping. My brain and mouth didn't work. I felt like inside my body was shaking. But visibly, outside, was nothing. At that time, I was managing diabetes and I figured it was related to victoza being stopped since I'm not a diabetic now. And it continued about 7 days. Then, dwindled for a few, but it returned. I then began getting panicked about it and having panic attacks. I'm afraid of dementia, and remembering was an issue.  It continued 4 days off 4 days on. Oddly enough. The 3rd week, it went away about 3 days in. I had about 7 days of bliss, but on the 4th day I got vaccination number 2. At this point, troubleshooting, I quit all my medications. I thought the issue was meditation related. I got shot number two and 3 days later, it hit and stayed again. 4 days on. 4 days off. By this time, I figured it is not my medications. So I went to my Dr. We did an MRI. Carotid workup. We did every test known to man, inluding heavy metals and found no anomalies except I was dehydrated. So I increased water and raised kidney functions. Weeks went by like this. Off and on. Dr finally told me I had toxic metabolic encephalopathy and I could have died. All testing rules out everything except vaccination reactions. He said my body didn't recognize the vaccine and that my brain attacked the toxins and swellee and caused the TME because of that. I want others to know. TMEs can be deadly. Your brain can swell, and you can die. Fortunately I'm on the upswing. But I still worry about memory. I forget appointments.  I still am for the vaccinations. But we never know how our own bodies will react. My physicians diagnosis is a TME caused by Pfizer vaccine. He has ruled everything else out.  I advocate this vaccinaction. Do it. I think what I went through is rare. But interestingly enough, online, it states 23 percent of covid victims get TME.  I didn't have Covid. I've tested negative. This is also not dementia or anything of that nature. I've been thoroughly examined.
LAB_DATA: Mri Heavy Metal test He did a lot. I don't know but blood and urine and a carotid arterial test and ekg

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Today 4/15/21, patient was administered the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. Prior to the vaccination, his wife mentioned to us that he has a severe phobia of needles and has passed out previously to other shots. He had no other issues on his PQCF preventing him from receiving the vaccine.  The PQCF was reviewed with the patient by pharmacist. Tech administered the vaccine under supervision of both pharmacist and other technician due to his phobia. Patient received the vaccine with no issues except obvious nerves and a few minutes later while still in the booth, he reported not feeling well. We got him a bottle of water and he went to the post-vaccination waiting area with his wife. We were monitoring him closely and noted that his head was slumping into his wife's stomach when he was sitting down, and he appeared ill. Immediately, we got patient in supine position on the floor with his feet on a chair elevated. Cold ice packs were put on his head, beck, and wrists. Within 5-10 minutes, he was feeling much better. He sat back up in the chair, still with ice packs, and drank water.  Patient was asked to stay for 30 minutes so we could continue to monitor him. After 30 minutes, he left with no issues.
CUR_ILL: previous COVID positive within last month not precluding him from getting vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the vaccine and was unknowingly pregnant. My first shot was on 1/6/2021 and my second shot was on 1/27/2021. I conceived on  1/25/2021. I ended up miscarrying the child and when they sent it in for testing it had 2 abnormal chromosomes. One of which they said is very rare and they have no idea how or why the baby had this. I was told that the vaccine was supposed to be safe for pregnant people but with no family history of anything like this happening and no history of any children being born with mutations I believe this happened from the vaccine. Possibly caused by the spike in temperature I experienced after the second shot. I should have been due to deliver 10/2021.
LAB_DATA: The fetus tested positive for Trisomy 15 and Trisomy 21. Trisomy 15 I was told is extremely rare and it is very odd to have both Trisomy 15 and 21. The baby stopped growing at 6 weeks and 3 days. At which point I had to attend multiple ultrasounds to ensure the fetus did not have a heartbeat. After 3 weeks of testing I had to have the fetus surgically removed because my body was not recognizing that the fetus was no longer living and was not rejecting it.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA  Patient received Janssen vaccine 4/9/2021. Patient presented to ED 4/14/2021. Patient is a very pleasant 32-year-old  female, with past medical history significant for taking bromocriptine for prolactin issues as well as metformin for type 2 diabetes, presents to the emergency department for evaluation of continued headache over the last 1 week.  Patient also reports chills, sweats, body aches ever since receiving the Johnson and Johnson coronavirus vaccination 1 week ago.  The headache started after receiving the vaccination and has been continuing ever since.  It does not fluctuate in intensity.  It is caused her blurred vision and difficulty focusing.  No tinnitus or hearing loss.  No slurred speech, vomiting, numbness or weakness or tingling to the extremities or any facial droop.  No history of strokes or aneurysms.  She is not on blood thinning medication at all.  No upper nor lower extremity swelling or redness.  No abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting or diarrhea.  She reports the continued subtle shortness of breath and body aches since the vaccination as well.  No rapid heart rate, long flights, long car rides, surgeries nor oral contraceptive use. Patient started on heparin drip. Neurologist recommended transferring patient to higher level of care. emergency department physician is willing to accept the patient at their facility.  Patient transferred to the facility.
LAB_DATA: EXAM:   MRA VENO HEAD W/WO C  INDICATION:   Other- Note in Reason For Exam FreeText. Worsening headache and blurred vision status post recent Johnson and Johnson vaccine menstruation  COMPARISON:   None.  TECHNIQUE:   MR venogram of the head performed without and with 10 cc gadolinium based IV contrast. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 78 year old woman admitted with severe back pain, inability to ambulate and leukocytosis on 3/31/21. History of hypertension, CHF, obesity, chronic kidney disease, and back pain. Work up included multiple consults. The patient was placed on SQ heparin for VTE prophylaxis. Acute L5 fracture was found along with emphysematous changes. Neurosurgical evaluation- no surgery was necessary. During the first 24 hours (before receiving the vaccine), the patient's Hg dropped 9.3 to 6.8 and platelets dropped 130K to 61 K with no apparent bleeding source.  PRBC transfusion was given. GI consult was obtained the patient was scheduled to have EGD the following morning (day 3). Cardiology was obtained for elevated troponin and hypoxia. An echo obtained on day 2 showed moderate elevated pulmonary artery pressure, mild to moderate tricuspid regurgitation, and normal sized right atrium and ventricle. The patient received the Janssen vaccine upon request the morning of hospital day 2 (4.1.21 at 11:02). At 11:37PM on 4/1/21 the patient received 5mg IV metoprolol for elevated HR of 132 (BP 129/67). At 0128 on 4/2/21 the patient's heart rate dropped into the 60's and then declined further requiring cardiac resuscitation. The attempt was unsuccessful and the patient expired at 01:43 on 4/2/21. An autopsy was conducted (results available on 4/13/21) showed a 4 cm clot in the patient's right atrium and a mural thrombus in her femoral artery.
LAB_DATA: Hg dropped from 9.3 on admission to 6.8 and subsequently 6.4 with no apparent bleeding source. Platelets dropped from 130K to 61K to 59K. WBC on admission was 22.9; troponin rose on day 2 from 0.067 to 0.174. Procalcitonin 0.95 on admission increased to 1.40 on day 2. BNP on day 2 was 157.
CUR_ILL: To ED with acute back pain, constipation, recent root canal, had received tramadol and Medrol dosepak at Urgent Care
HISTORY: Hypertension, congestive heart failure, obesity, back pain, chronic kidney disease not requiring dialysis

Pt presented to clinic today for his 2nd dose Moderna vaccine at approx 1033.  Pt was brought back to conference room and was given his 2nd dose Moderna vaccine at approx 1040.  Pt reported no allergies to medications, no severe allergic reaction in the past.  Pt states doing fine with the 1st dose of the Moderna vaccine.  Pt was waiting his observation time of 15 min and began itching face, arms, and legs.  Nurse questioned pt if he was feeling ok? If he is itching?  Pt reports that he is itching but he has some anxiety but that he is hanging in there. Nurse offered pt some water.  Pt declined.   Pt started clearing throat and coughing.  Nurse questioned pt if he was still feeling ok and again offered pt some water.  Pt declined.  Pt reports that he is feeling ok.  Pt's timer alarmed and pt got up ready to leave.  When asked if he is doing ok, pt reports that he is.  Nurse questioned pt if his cough is normal for him and pt reports that he has asthma and proceeded to walk out.  Pt was escorted by nurse.  Nurse questioned pt again if he is feeling ok.  Pt states that he is.  Nurse notifies pt that if he not feeling ok then he should come back.  Pt states understanding and exits building.  Nurse seen pt returning back to clinic from window. Nurse meets pt upon entering building.  Pt reports trouble breathing. Nurse observes that pt has voice change, trouble completing sentences, cough is worsening, and itching is intensified.  Pt grabs the wall while ambulating.  Nurse provided stand by assist.  Nurse immediately escorts pt back to exam room and gets assistance from nursing staff and provider presents to exam room immediately.   Crash cart arrives.  Epi 0.3mg autoinjector administered  IM to LT at approx 1100.  IV NS ordered. At approx 1104 pt O2 sat of 98% on RA, HR 96. Approx 1105 Duo Neb administered via nebulizer mask as ordered.  Approx 1107 IV inserted to RAC with 18g on 2nd attempt. Approx 1108 Diphenhydramine 25mg/0.5ml administered IV as ordered. SoluMedrol 125mg/2ml administered IV as ordered.  Pt O2 sat 97% on RA, HR 102.  Approx 1110 pt BP 140/85, O2 sat of 93% on RA. Pt has coughing spell. EMS was called.  Approx 1113 pt O2 sat 90% on RA.  Ongoing coughing spell. Approx 1114 O2 2L administered via mask as orderd by provider.  Pt's wife contacted via pt's cell phone.  Approx 1116 Epi 0.3mg administered IM to LT as ordered.  Pt O2 sat 97% on 2L O2, HR 87.  Pt reports itching getting worse.  Approx 1121 Diphendydramine 25mg/0.5ml administered IV as ordered. Approx 1123 pt O2 sat 97% on 2L O2, HR 119.  Approx 1125 EMS arrived.  Approx 1127 BP 183/75.  Pt taken by ambulance with EMS to ER at approx 1135.  Report called to ER by provider.  ER transfer form faxed to ER.

The first dose of the Pfizer vaccine was taken on March 15th at 8:30. Within a week I started feeling weak joints, headaches followed by a sharp pain on the occipital lobe. I started my period for the second time that month, which was odd because it never happened to me before. I went to work that week, but by Friday (March 30th) I was not able to handle the pain so after work I went to the doctor and they took blood to see if there was anything going on. The result came back the following day and everything was normal. I was given medicine (muscle relaxers) for the occipital pain, but it was not enough. At that time I was not sure what was the cause of it, I thought it was a bad flu, but I didn't come to the conclusion that it was because of the vaccine, because a week had passed by, so I thought it was impossible. The doctor asked for me to take an X-Ray for the occipital pain, so I did (March 30th) and it resulted in everything being fine. She also recommended for me to get an abdominal ultrasound to see if my uterus was fine due to the second period. I currently took the second Pfizer dose in the same location, but this time around I felt all of these symptoms within 3 hours of the vaccination. I started feeling lightheaded and dazed, my joints started feeling weak, my mouth and tongue started feeling sensitive (fever blisters and sensitive to anything that is acidic, spicy, etc).  I have not visited the doctor this time around because the pain is tolerable. I have noticed in increase of joint pain as the days go by.
LAB_DATA: Bloodwork for general exam on March 27th, 2021. X-Ray for pain on occipital lobe on March 30th, 2021. Abdominal Ultrasound to check uterus on March 31st, 2021.

The pain started about an hour later, but at that point it was mild and only notable because of the quick onset and slightly different feel from the first dose. I saw my primary care physician the next morning, he confirmed the positioning of the injection was incorrect. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client had a chief complaint of chest pain. Client stated that she began feeling chest pain several minutes after the start of her observation. Client has a history of depression and other unspecified psychiatric illnesses. Client stated that she takes sertraline daily and has a history of taking Risperdal. Client stated that she regularly sees a Psychiatrist. Client denied any allergies or other underlying medical illnesses. Assessment revealed chest pain located in the center of the patient?s chest. Client pointed to her sternum to indicate the exact location and stated that her arms felt "heavy." Client's airway, breathing and circulation were intact, however, client complained of shortness of breath. Client was alert and oriented to person, place, date and event while appearing slightly distractible. 02 saturation 100%. Client was negative for redness, swelling, hives, severe sweating or other signs or symptoms of anaphylaxis. Client denied any increase in chest pain or shortness of breath when breathing in or out and did not state any additional pain throughout her body. Client then added that she felt "anxious" after receiving her shot and stated some reluctance with even receiving the shot prior to her arrival. Client's mother was present and stated that client had been reading the Pfizer fact sheet she was given and had been focusing on the side effects portion before signaling for assistance. Client's initial vitals were as follows: Blood pressure:138/88, Pulse 76, Respirations 20, O2 sat 100%, Eyes equal and reactive to light, Lung sounds clear bilaterally. Client initially consented to staying an additional 30 minutes. She began to become anxious and impatient with her additional observation time. After 10 minutes of sitting the client began stating that she was afraid that her "heart would become too "fast" when she got home if she "didn't throw it away." After some encouragement, the client was able to clarify "it" as "meth" which she had hidden at home. Client stated some reluctance to go home stating that if she smoked her "meth" that her heart rate would become too "fast." Client then asked EMT if he was willing to come home with her to help her "throw it away." All staff present praised the client for sharing this information and after discussing her concerns further, client became much calmer and stated that she felt much safer and that her chest pain, shortness of breath and anxiety had subsided. Client then stated that she wanted to go home but consented to a second set of vitals before leaving. All of the client's vitals improved: blood pressure 132/88, pulse 68, respirations 16, O2 sat 98%. 1636 - 138/88, 76, 20, 100% 1651 - 132/88, 68, 16, 98%. Client was encouraged to discuss the incident with her psychiatrist and to seek further counseling. Client was also instructed to seek further medical care or the emergency room if symptoms returned. No medications were administered.
OTHER_MEDS: Sertraline and history of taking Risperdal
HISTORY: History of depression and other unspecified Psychiatric Illnesses

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I gave the vaccine around 6:20pm after counseling on possible adverse reactions and going over the patient's questions. I then asked them to wait 15min. Within 5-10mins the patient got up and came back to our counter saying he thinks he's having a reaction. I pulled him back into our vaccination area and had him sit down and explain what he was feeling to me. He looked pale and told me he felt dizzy, sweaty, shaky, & nauseous. He wanted me to grab him a bag incase he puked. I grabbed a bag as well as water and Benadryl. I asked if he was having any issues breathing or if it felt like his tongue was swollen at all. He said no issues breathing and tongue felt fine.  He started to feel better within about 10-15 minutes after onset. He did not puke and his color returned. I had him wait an additional 10-15 minutes after that to make sure we were recovered. I asked him if there was anything else going on and he mentioned that he hadn't slept well the night before and that he had barely eaten today. He also mentioned he can get anxiety. I told him all of those factors could certainly contribute to what he just experienced but that I would be reporting this on to be safe.
CUR_ILL: No illnesses. After the fact we discussed pt hadn't slept much the night before and hadn't eaten much the day of, which we discussed could definitely have contributed.

The numbness can be painful as a sudden thrust in an arm ( this does not last more than a few seconds).  It has now been going on since week 3 of my first dosis and today is day 7 of my second dosis! SYMPTOM_TEXT: Main symptom: Around 10 hours after receiving the vaccine, my right ankle felt slightly numb. I also had a sharp, painful shooting pain in the middle of the sole of my foot that lasted less than a second. As the night progressed, the numb area spread slowly to other parts of my foot.  When I woke up the following day (today), I was surprised to discover I was not only still numb, but the numbness had spread across the entire outside of my right foot (from my ankle to 3/4 of the distance to my pinky toe).   Now, several hours later at 8:30pm, the numbness reaches all the way from near my pinky toe on my right foot up to the bottom of my calf. All of the numbness is isolated to the right side of my right lower extremities and has not crossed over to the middle of any of my extremities yet.   I can also feel a slight numb sensation in my left index finger stretching to the base of my left thumb, but it isn't nearly as bad as my right foot. I haven't felt any addition sharp shooting pains.  Numbness aside, I had a pretty bad headache from about 4pm to 10pm yesterday, and when I closed my eyes saw what appeared to be mild hallucinations (green and red streaks that disappeared pretty quickly, and were only visible when my eyes were closed). I'm no longer having the visual symptoms, but the numbness is getting worse by the hour.  I have NEVER had any of these symptoms before in my life, and did nothing out of the ordinary yesterday or today in terms of food or physical activities. I take no medications.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pulmonary emboli. Patient with history of bilateral pulmonary emboli, "heavy burden". Patient presented to ER with 2 days of progressive dyspnea. She also noticed significant edema in the feet. She was evaluated at ER and found on CTA of the chest to have pulmonary emboli, transferred to hospital where she was evaluated and treated further. She does not remember the details of her visit. We are attempting to get a discharge summary from facility. She was discharged home on Eliquis 10 mg twice daily for several days and is now on 5 mg twice daily. She stopped her daily baby aspirin use. On presentation to ER she had hypotension, tachycardia, hypoxia. She also had the self described marked pedal edema. On examination today she is normotensive with normal heart rate and normal O2 saturation at 96%. Also she has no edema in the ankles/feet. No JVD. She seems to had a split second heart sound on inhalation, otherwise normal cardiac exam. She continues with some excessive dyspnea on exertion, but improved. Her only apparent risk for blood clotting is her BMI of 34.5. She does have history of essential thrombocytosis but her count is normalized on therapy. Also, she has been taking baby aspirin daily prior to hospital admission, interestingly, she did received the Moderna vaccination, first dose January 22, 2021, second dose February 24, 2021. Her dyspnea on exertion began 8 days later, 2 days after the dyspnea began she presented to the emergency room March 6, 2021.   No other complaints.  Physical exam:  General: No acute distress.  Skin: Anicteric. Nondiaphoretic.  Neck: No JVD.  Thorax: Symmetic.  Lungs: Clear with good breath sounds throughout.  Cardiovascular: Regular rate and rhythm without significant murmur, rub gallop. She does seem to have a split second heart sound with inhalation. Otherwise, S1 and S2 Instensity normal. No heaves.  Abdomen: Positive normal bowel sounds. Nondistended. No tinkles or rushes. No bruits.  Back and extremities: Without clubbing, cyanosis, or edema.  Neurologic: Alert and oriented x4. Cranial nerves grossly intact. Ambulates and transfers normally.  Psychologic: Mood is good. Affect is normal.  Assessment and plan:  Bilateral pulmonary emboli, heavy burden: Symptoms began 8 days after her last dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccination. Clinically markedly improved except continues with dyspnea on exertion. We will check echocardiogram. She will return to office 1 week after echo is performed. She will get in touch with hematology ASAP. Continue NOAC therapy for 3 to 6 months. Remain off aspirin for now.  Essential thrombocytosis: Counts have been normalized with treatment.
ALLERGIES: Gabapentin, Iodine, Tineture swab, penicillins, zestril
